To read these tables:

  1. We infused the media with antibiotics from 17 Pseudonocardia lines that had been collected from different ant colonies (A-S), plus a non-infused control media. There are potentially genetic differences among these vertically transmitted lineages, so we call them: Ps.strain

  2. We measured growth rates of 10 strains of Streptomyces (1-10) and 10 strains of Softbugs (11-20). These are invading strains so we call them: Inv.strain.

  3. Each of the (17 * 20 =) 340 combinations of Ps.strain and Inv.strain was repeated 3 times for a total sample size of (340 * 3 =) 1020 treatment inoculations and 60 control inoculations, but some colonies could not be scored due to difficulties in reading colony area, leaving us with (170 + 292 =) 462 Streptomyces inoculations and (149 + 304 =) 453 Softbugs inoculations. 462 + 453 = 915 total treatment inoculations + (20 * 3 =) 60 control inoculations = 975 total inoculations.

  4. Thus, the experiment is fully crossed but somewhat imbalanced at the end.

  5. (510 - 462 =) 48 Streptomyces inoculations and (510 - 453 =) 57 Softbug inoculations could not be scored. Note that we did score cases where there was no growth.

To read these boxplots:

  1. The y-axis is the final area (cm2) of the colony inoculated onto the plate (the notional ‘invader’)

  2. On control media (left 2 columns), Soft-bug colonies (blue) grow bigger (more quickly) than do Streptomyces colonies (orange).

  3. However, on Pseudonocardia-infused media (Ps1, Ps2), Streptomyces colonies (orange) grow more quickly than do soft-bug colonies (blue).

  4. The 17 Pseudonocardia colonies (Ps.strain) used to infuse the media can be usefully divided into two 16S genotypes (Ps1 n = 6, Ps2 n = 11). Growth rates of Streptomyces and softbugs appear lower on the Ps2 infusions (i.e. Ps2 appears to be a more effective inhibitor in general).

  5. There are fewer Control datapoints because this represents only one kind of media, whereas the Pseudonocardia (Ps1 and Ps2) treatment represents 17 Ps lineages.

  6. The empty triangles are all from Softbug strain 18, clearly demonstrating the existence of correlated residuals in the Inv.strain variable.

Start of analysis.

There are two potential random factors:

  1. Pseudonocardia strains: Ps.strain (17 levels: A-S)
  2. Invader strains: Inv.strain (20 levels: labeled 1-20). 1-10 are Streptomyces strains, 11-20 are Softbug strains

There are 3 Plate replicates for each combination of Ps.strain and Inv.strain, and each of the 20 Inv.strains is tested against each of the 17 Ps.strains. Some complexity: not all inoculations were scorable, so were omitted. This is a fully crossed but somewhat imbalanced experiment

There are 2 fixed factors:

  1. Pseuonocardia genotype: Ps.genotype (Ps1, Ps2).
  2. Invader type: Invader (softbugs, Streptomyces)

Finally, the response variable is:

  1. Mean colony area (cm2): Invasion.score

Construct a full model and test for an interaction effect of medium (Ps.genotype) and Invader (Streptomyces and Softbugs) and also test for correlated residuals in each of the potential random factors

M1 <- lm(Invasion.score~Invader*Ps.genotype, data=assay3)
E1 <- rstandard(M1)
plot(E1 ~ assay3$Ps.strain); abline(0,0) # T,P,Q strains either mostly above or below 0, demonstrating correlated residuals for some strains

plot(E1 ~ assay3$Inv.strain); abline(0,0) # 11,14,16,17,18,19,20,4,5,9,10 either mostly above or below 0, demonstrating correlated residuals for some strains. recall that 11-20 are softbugs and 1-10 are _Streptomyces_

rm(M1)
rm(E1)

Thus, we use a model with random factors. In particular, note that Softbug strain 18 has a high growth rate, which we saw in the boxplot (empty triangle points)

# with interaction effect
M1 <- lmer(Invasion.score ~ Invader * Ps.genotype + (1|Ps.strain/Plate) + (1|Inv.strain), data=assay3, REML = FALSE)
# without interaction effect
M2 <- lmer(Invasion.score ~ Invader + Ps.genotype + (1|Ps.strain/Plate) + (1|Inv.strain), data=assay3, REML = FALSE)

anova(M1, M2) # highly significant interaction effect:  p = 1.102e-10

Effect of Ps1 vs Ps2

From the Andersen et al. (2013) results, we hypothesised that Ps2 would be a stronger growth suppressor than is Ps1.

Remove the Control level and test again for a significant main effect of Ps.genotype (Ps1 vs Ps2).

assay4 <- assay3 %>% dplyr::filter(Ps.genotype != "Control")
assay4$Ps.genotype <- fct_drop(assay4$Ps.genotype)
